Salinas and Jobos BESS Invoice Calculator
=========================================

This project calculates monthly compensation for the Salinas and Jobos BESS
contract and reports selected Appendix P performance-guarantee damages.

The current calculator is built around Appendix F monthly compensation, with
Appendix P values reported separately so they can be reviewed before deciding
whether they should be netted through `ADJ` or invoice presentation.


What It Calculates
------------------

Monthly compensation:

- `CPP = CPPF + CPPPIF`
- `MCC`, including approved Performance Test adjustments
- `FA`
- `FAA`
- `PRA`
- `MFP = CPP x MCC x FAA x PRA`
- `MP = MFP - ADJ`

Performance guarantee reporting:

- `ALD` Availability Liquidated Damages
- `Actual_Efficiency`
- `ELD` Efficiency Liquidated Damages
- `CLD_per_day` formula exists, but total monthly CLD allocation is not wired yet

`MP` is currently reduced by `ALD` and `ELD` through `ADJ_Total`, based on the
working assumption that Appendix F `ADJ` includes other credits or amounts to
which PREPA has a right under the Agreement. `CLD` is not included yet because
total CLD allocation across the failed-test/cure period is not implemented.


Input Files
-----------

Primary files used by `main.py`:

| File | Purpose |
| --- | --- |
| `data/bess_contract_values_template.csv` | Contract values by Agreement Year: `CPPF`, `CPPPIF`, `DDD`, `TA`, `RER`, `GE`, and design values |
| `data/bess_yearly_inputs_template.csv` | Yearly values: `DDE` and fallback/manual `TR` |
| `data/bess_monthly_inputs_template.csv` | Monthly compensation inputs: `ADJ`, availability hours, and PREPA risk hours |
| `data/Monthly_Performance_Guarantee.csv` | Monthly metered efficiency inputs: `CE`, `DE`, `AE_beg`, `AE_end` |
| `data/Performance_Tests.csv` | Event-based performance tests: `TDE`, ramp rate, test date, approval status, and cure/retest fields |

The current code still reads the `bess_*_template.csv` files for the main
compensation path. The friendlier sample names may be useful for review, but
they are not the active inputs unless `main.py` is changed.


Important Contract Modeling Decisions
-------------------------------------

`DDE` is currently a yearly input.

Contractually, Degraded Duration Energy means Design Duration Energy adjusted
downward by the applicable Energy Degradation Factor and adjusted upward by
qualifying Performance Tests after maintenance or technology upgrades, capped
at Design Duration Energy. The calculator does not derive that yet.

`TDE` is the performance-test source value.

Approved Performance Tests can affect `MCC`. The adjustment starts on the first
day of the Billing Period after the Billing Period in which the Performance Test
occurred.

Current MCC behavior:

- If an approved applicable Performance Test exists, use Appendix F Section 3(c):
  - if `TDE < 0.99 x DDE`, then `MCC = TDE / DDD`
  - otherwise `MCC = DDE / DDD`
- If no approved applicable Performance Test exists, use fallback `TR`:
  - `MCC = min(DDE / DDD, TR)`


Run It
------

```powershell
python .\main.py
```

Output is written to:

```text
output/bess_monthly_results.csv
```


Report Structure Target
-----------------------

Section 10.1 gives the practical checklist for the future written invoice or
`report.txt`. Each Billing Period report should include, as applicable:

- Monthly Fixed Payment
- Other Payment Adjustments
- Discharge Energy
- Charge Energy
- Ancillary Services
- Green Credits
- Balance
- information necessary to determine Facility performance
- insurance payments
- credits or payments owing to PREPA
- itemized statement of all other charges under the Agreement

That means the current result columns should eventually be presented as an
invoice-style report, not only a calculation table. A useful first structure is:

1. Billing Period and Agreement Year
2. Monthly Fixed Payment calculation: `CPP`, `MCC`, `FAA`, `PRA`, `MFP`
3. Other Payment Adjustments and Monthly Payment: `Other_ADJ`, `ALD`, `ELD`, `ADJ_Total`, `MP`
4. Metered performance data: `CE`, `DE`, `Actual_Efficiency`
5. Performance guarantee items: `ALD`, `ELD`, and later `CLD`
6. PREPA credits/payments and itemized charges
7. Net invoice presentation, once treatment of LDs versus `ADJ` is settled


Known Gaps
----------

- `DDE` is not yet derived from degradation factors or qualifying upgrade tests.
- `TR` remains as a fallback input while performance-test timing is being proven.
- Performance Test MCC currently uses only `prepa_approved = TRUE` tests. This
  follows the Section 6.9 approval process, but Appendix F Section 3(c) says the
  adjustment continues until another Performance Test is completed, so the exact
  approval-versus-completion trigger should be confirmed.
- Annual adjustment replacement is modeled by Agreement Year. If an annual
  adjustment can occur mid-Agreement-Year, that timing is not yet represented.
- `ALD` and `ELD` are folded into `ADJ_Total` under the current working assumption.
  Confirm that source `ADJ` data excludes calculated LDs to avoid double-counting.
- `CLD_per_day` is available, but total CLD allocation across failed-test and
  cure/retest dates still needs implementation.
- Ramp-rate failure currently belongs in performance-test data, but its outage
  consequence is not yet automatically rolled into `UNAVHRS`.
